7 9.5–303.
8 (a) The State Board shall adopt regulations that relate to the registration of
9 family child care homes and large family child care homes.
10 (b) So far as practicable, the regulations shall be uniform with the rules and
11 regulations adopted by other State agencies as those rules and regulations relate to other
12 types of child care.
13 (c) At a minimum, the regulations shall provide for:
14 (1) Minimum standards of environmental health and safety, including
15 provisions for:
16 (i) Adequate and safe physical surroundings, including
17 requirements for window coverings in accordance with § 5–505 of the Family Law Article;
18 (ii) The physical and mental health of child care providers; [and]
19 (iii) Investigation of any criminal record of a child care provider; AND
20 (IV) MAINTAINING EMERGENCY INFORMATION FROM A CHILD’S
21 PARENT OR GUARDIAN THAT IS UPDATED AS NEEDED AND REVIEWED BY THE
22 PARENT OR GUARDIAN AT LEAST ONCE EACH YEAR;
23 (2) A thorough evaluation of each prospective family child care home, large
24 family child care home, and child care provider, to be completed before the Department
25 accepts an initial registration;
26 (3) An initial family child care registration that expires 2 years after its
27 effective date;
28 (4) A continuing family child care registration that:
29 (i) Upon application by the child care provider that meets the
30 requirements set by the Department, is issued to the provider before the end of the initial
31 registration period; and

HOUSE BILL 1574 7
1 (ii) Once issued, remains in effect until surrendered, suspended,
2 revoked, or replaced by a conditional registration;
3 (5) Reporting of any changed circumstances that relate to the
4 requirements, by the child care provider, at the time the change occurs;
5 (6) An orientation to be provided to prospective child care providers by the
6 Department before initial registration;
7 (7) Announced inspection by the Department of each registered family
8 child care home and large family child care home prior to issuance of an initial or continuing
9 registration to determine whether applicable requirements are being met;
10 (8) Unannounced inspection by the Department of each registered family
11 child care home and large family child care home at least once during each 12–month period
12 that an initial or continuing registration is in effect to determine whether safe and
13 appropriate child care is being provided;
14 (9) Procedures to be followed by the Department in response to a complaint
15 about a family child care home or large family child care home THAT:
16 (I) MAKE USE OF A UNIFORM COMPLAINT INTAKE PROCESS;
17 AND
18 (II) IMPLEMENT ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2027, IMPLEMENT A
19 STANDARDIZED COMPLAINT PRIORITY GUIDE THAT DIFFERENTIATES COMPLAINTS
20 BY THE SERIOUSNESS OF THE ISSUE RAISED, INCLUDING DEFINED RESPONSE TIMES
21 FOR EACH LEVEL OF COMPLAINT;
22 (10) A requirement that each registered child care provider shall hold a
23 current certificate indicating successful completion of approved:
24 (i) Basic first aid training through the American Red Cross or
25 through a program with equivalent standards; and
26 (ii) Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training through the
27 American Heart Association or through a program with equivalent standards appropriate
28 for the ages of children for whom care is provided in the family child care home or large
29 family child care home;
30 (11) A requirement that the minimum age of a family child care teacher in
31 a registered large family child care home be at least 18 years old and that an individual not
32 be precluded from being a family child care teacher solely for being 18 years old;

8 HOUSE BILL 1574
1 (12) (i) A requirement that a family child care home or large family child
2 care home that receives notice of a contaminated drinking water supply from the family
3 child care home’s or large family child care home’s supplier of water, in accordance with §
4 9–410 of the Environment Article or otherwise, send notice of the drinking water
5 contamination to the parent or legal guardian of each child attending the family child care
6 home or large family child care home; and
7 (ii) A requirement that the notice sent by the family child care home
8 or large family child care home shall:
9 1. Be sent within 10 business days after receipt of the notice
10 of contamination from the family child care home’s or large family child care home’s water
11 supplier;
12 2. Be in writing;
13 3. Identify the contaminants and their levels in the family
14 child care home’s or large family child care home’s water supply; and
15 4. Describe the family child care home’s or large family child
16 care home’s plan for dealing with the water contamination problem until the family child
17 care home’s or large family child care home’s water is determined by the appropriate
18 authority to be safe for consumption; and
19 (13) A requirement that a family child care home or large family child care
20 home prohibit the administration of corporal punishment to discipline a child.
21 (d) The State Board shall adopt regulations that:
22 (1) Require a family child care provider to have a written emergency
23 preparedness plan for emergency situations that require evacuation, sheltering in place, or
24 other protection of children such as in the event of fire, natural disaster, or other
25 threatening situation that may pose a health or safety hazard to the children in the family
26 child care home or large family child care home;
27 (2) Require the plan under item (1) of this subsection to include:
28 (i) A designated relocation site and evacuation route;
29 (ii) Procedures for notifying parents or other adults responsible for
30 the child of the relocation;
31 (iii) Procedures to address the needs of individual children including
32 children with special needs;
33 (iv) Procedures for the reassignment of staff duties during an
34 emergency, as appropriate; and

