26 RULE OR REGULATION; AND
27 (II) FOR SUBSEQUENT VIOLATIONS, THE DEPARTMENT MAY
28 IMPOSE ON THE LICENSEE OR LETTER HOLDER A PENALTY AUTHORIZED UNDER
29 THIS TITLE.
30 (c) (1) Except as otherwise provided in subsection (d) of this section, before
31 any action is taken under this section, the State Superintendent shall give the individual
32 against whom the action is contemplated an opportunity for a public hearing before the
33 State Superintendent.

16 HOUSE BILL 1574
1 (2) The hearing notice to be given to the individual shall be sent at least 10
2 days before the hearing.
3 (3) The individual may be represented at the hearing by counsel.
4 (d) (1) (i) The State Superintendent may suspend the license or letter of
5 compliance to operate a child care center on an emergency basis when the State
6 Superintendent determines that this action is required to protect the health, safety, or
7 welfare of a child in the child care center.
8 (ii) When the State Superintendent suspends a license or letter of
9 compliance on an emergency basis, the State Superintendent shall deliver written notice of
10 the suspension to the licensee stating the regulatory basis for the suspension.
11 (2) (i) Upon delivery of the emergency suspension notice, the licensee
12 or letter holder shall cease immediately operation of the child care center.
13 (ii) The licensee or letter holder may request a hearing before the
14 State Superintendent.
15 (3) (i) If a hearing is requested by the licensee or letter holder, the State
16 Superintendent shall hold a hearing within 7 calendar days of the request for a hearing.
17 The hearing shall be held in accordance with the Administrative Procedure Act.
18 (ii) Within 7 calendar days of the hearing a decision concerning the
19 emergency suspension shall be made by the State Superintendent.
20 (4) If the emergency suspension order is upheld by the State
21 Superintendent, the licensee or letter holder shall continue to cease operations until it is
22 determined that the health, safety, or welfare of a child in the child care center is no longer
23 threatened.
24 (5) Any person aggrieved by a decision of the State Superintendent to
25 uphold an emergency suspension may appeal that decision directly to the circuit court in
26 the county in which the child care center is located.
27 (e) The State Superintendent may petition the circuit court in the county in which
28 the child care center is located to enjoin the activities and operations of a person who
29 operates a child care center without a license or letter of compliance as required by this
30 subtitle, including when a license or letter of compliance has been denied, revoked, or
31 suspended in accordance with this subtitle.
32 9.5–411.1.
33 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
34 INDICATED.

HOUSE BILL 1574 17
1 (2) “MARYLAND EXCELS” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 9.5–306.1
2 OF THIS TITLE.
3 (3) “PUBLISHED” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 9.5–306.1 OF THIS
4 TITLE.
5 (4) “QUALITY RATING” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 9.5–306.1 OF
6 THIS TITLE.
7 (B) IF THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES THAT A CHILD CARE CENTER WITH
8 A PUBLISHED MARYLAND EXCELS QUALITY RATING HAS VIOLATED A
9 REQUIREMENT OF THIS TITLE OR A RULE OR REGULATION ADOPTED UNDER THIS
10 TITLE, THE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY SHALL NOTIFY THE OPERATOR OF THE
11 CHILD CARE CENTER OF THE VIOLATION.
12 (C) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE OPERATOR OF THE CHILD CARE CENTER
13 SHALL ENTER INTO AN AGREEMENT THAT DESCRIBES:
14 (1) THE NATURE OF THE VIOLATION;
15 (2) THE ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN BY THE CHILD CARE CENTER TO
16 BECOME COMPLIANT; AND
17 (3) A PLAN FOR FOLLOW–UP BY THE DEPARTMENT TO ENSURE THAT
18 THE CHILD CARE CENTER HAS RETURNED TO AND REMAINS FULLY COMPLIANT WITH
19 REQUIREMENTS OF THIS TITLE OR A RULE OR REGULATION THAT WAS PREVIOUSLY
20 VIOLATED.
21 (D) (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION,
22 THE DEPARTMENT MAY REDUCE OR RESCIND A PUBLISHED MARYLAND EXCELS
23 QUALITY RATING IF THE CHILD CARE CENTER:
24 (I) FAILS TO COMPLY WITH THE TERMS OF THE AGREEMENT OR
25 OTHERWISE FAILS TO CURE THE INITIAL VIOLATION; OR
26 (II) FAILS OR REFUSES TO ENTER INTO AN AGREEMENT.
27 (2) IF THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES THAT THE VIOLATION DID NOT
28 INVOLVE AN IMMEDIATE RISK TO CHILD SAFETY AND THE CHILD CARE CENTER
29 TIMELY RETURNED TO COMPLIANCE, THE DEPARTMENT MAY NOT REDUCE THE
30 PUBLISHED MARYLAND EXCELS QUALITY RATING OF THE CHILD CARE CENTER.

18 HOUSE BILL 1574
1 (E) IF THE DEPARTMENT REDUCES THE PUBLISHED MARYLAND EXCELS
2 QUALITY RATING OF A CHILD CARE CENTER, WITHIN 30 DAYS AFTER THE CENTER
3 RETURNS TO COMPLIANCE BY FULFILLING THE TERMS OF THE AGREEMENT
4 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
5 RESTORE THE PUBLISHED MARYLAND EXCELS QUALITY RATING OF THE CHILD
6 CARE CENTER TO THE QUALITY RATING EARNED BEFORE THE VIOLATION
7 OCCURRED.
8 (F) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION MAY BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT THE ABILITY
9 OF THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT TO SUSPEND A LICENSE OR LETTER OF
10 COMPLIANCE ON AN EMERGENCY BASIS TO PROTECT THE HEALTH, SAFETY, OR
11 WELFARE OF CHILDREN IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 9.5–411 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
12 9.5–411.2.
13 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “FAILURE TO SUPERVISE” MEANS THE FAILURE OF AN
14 INDIVIDUAL RESPONSIBLE FOR OVERSEEING THE WELL–BEING OF CHILDREN TO
15 MONITOR PROPERLY OR PROTECT THE CHILDREN IN THE INDIVIDUAL’S CARE.
16 (B) IF THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT DETERMINES THAT AN INDIVIDUAL
17 MAY NOT BE EMPLOYED BY A CHILD CARE OPERATOR DUE TO A FINDING OF A
18 FAILURE TO SUPERVISE, THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT SHALL PROVIDE WRITTEN
19 NOTICE TO THE INDIVIDUAL AND THE CHILD CARE CENTER OPERATOR THAT
20 INCLUDES:
21 (1) A STATEMENT OF THE FINDING; AND
22 (2) THE REASONS FOR THE FINDING.
23 (C) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL MAINTAIN A LIST OF INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE
24 PROHIBITED FROM EMPLOYMENT IN A CHILD CARE CENTER DUE TO A FAILURE TO
25 SUPERVISE UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION.
26 (D) (1) AN INDIVIDUAL PROHIBITED FROM EMPLOYMENT ON THE LIST
27 UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION MAY REQUEST A CONDUCT
28 REASSESSMENT AND REMOVAL FROM THE LIST IF THE INDIVIDUAL:
29 (I) SUBMITS A WRITTEN REQUEST TO THE DEPARTMENT,
30 INCLUDING ANY DOCUMENTATION REQUIRED BY THE DEPARTMENT;
31 (II) COMPLETES ACTIVE SUPERVISION TRAINING APPROVED BY
32 THE DEPARTMENT; AND

HOUSE BILL 1574 19
1 (III) COMPLETES ANY OTHER CORRECTIVE ACTIONS REQUIRED
2 BY THE DEPARTMENT.
3 (2) IF AN INDIVIDUAL UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION
4 COMPLETES THE REQUIREMENTS ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT TO THE
5 SATISFACTION OF THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT, THE INDIVIDUAL SHALL BE
6 REMOVED FROM THE LIST UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION AND ELIGIBLE
7 FOR EMPLOYMENT AT A CHILD CARE CENTER.
8 (E) IF THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT DETERMINES THAT A VIOLATION OF
9 THIS TITLE OR A RULE OR REGULATION ADOPTED UNDER THIS TITLE FOR A FAILURE
10 TO SUPERVISE WAS DUE ONLY TO THE CONDUCT OF AN INDIVIDUAL PROHIBITED
11 FROM EMPLOYMENT UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION, THE STATE
12 SUPERINTENDENT MAY NOT SANCTION THE CHILD CARE CENTER FOR THE
13 VIOLATION.
14 (F) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION MAY BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT THE ABILITY
15 OF THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT TO SUSPEND A LICENSE OR LETTER OF
16 COMPLIANCE ON AN EMERGENCY BASIS TO PROTECT THE HEALTH, SAFETY, OR
17 WELFARE OF CHILDREN IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 9.5–411 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
18 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
19 (a) There is a Workgroup to Study Illegally Provided Child Care.
20 (b) The Workgroup consists of the following members:
21 (1) two members of the Senate of Maryland, appointed by the President of
22 the Senate;
23 (2) two members of the House of Delegates, appointed by the Speaker of
24 the House;
25 (3) the State Superintendent of Schools, or the Superintendent’s designee;
26 (4) the Secretary of Human Services, or the Secretary’s designee;
27 (5) one representative of the Maryland Family Network, designated by the
28 Executive Director of the Maryland Family Network;
29 (6) one representative of the Maryland State Child Care Association,
30 designated by the President of the Maryland State Child Care Association;

20 HOUSE BILL 1574
1 (7) one representative of the Maryland State Family Child Care
2 Association, designated by the President of the Maryland State Family Child Care
3 Association;
4 (8) one representative of the Maryland Head Start Association, designated
5 by the President of the Maryland Head Start Association;
6 (9) one representative of the Latino Child Care Association of Maryland,
7 Inc., designated by the President of the Latino Child Care Association of Maryland, Inc.;
8 and
9 (10) the following members appointed by the Governor:
10 (i) two parents of children enrolled in the Child Care Scholarship
11 Program;
12 (ii) two representatives from child care providers that:
13 1. serve children under the age of 5 years; and
14 2. accept scholarships from the Child Care Scholarship
15 Program;
16 (iii) one representative of a labor union that represents child care
17 workers;
18 (iv) two representatives of law enforcement; and
19 (v) two nonvoting representatives of national child care policy
20 organizations with expertise in state child care financing models.
21 (c) The State Superintendent of Schools shall designate the chair of the
22 Workgroup.
23 (d) The State Department of Education shall provide staff for the Workgroup.
24 (e) A member of the Workgroup:
25 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Workgroup; but
26 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
27 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
28 (f) The Workgroup shall study and make recommendations about the scale and
29 impacts of illegally provided child care in the State, including:

HOUSE BILL 1574 21
1 (1) the number, geographic location, socioeconomic status, race, ethnicity,
2 and disability status of children who lack access to safe, regulated child care;
3 (2) the impact of illegally provided care on family child care homes, large
4 family child care homes, child care centers, and the child care industry as a whole;
5 (3) barriers to registration or licensure for child care providers and the best
6 practices to remove identified barriers, including greater assistance to providers, improved
7 communication between regulators and providers, or regulatory or statutory changes;
8 (4) the distinct, documented risks to the health and safety of children of
9 illegally provided child care and potential health and safety risks that illegally provided
10 child care could pose to children; and
11 (5) any legal changes necessary to prevent illegally provided child care,
12 including any statutory or regulatory changes necessary to ease the investigation and
13 enforcement of existing State law.
14 (g) (1) On or before January 1, 2027, the Workgroup shall submit an interim
15 report on its findings and recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with §
16 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly.
17 (2) On or before December 1, 2028, the Workgroup shall submit a final
18 report on its findings and recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with §
19 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly.
20 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
21 (a) The State Department of Education and the Office of the Child Care Advocacy
22 Council jointly shall review:
23 (1) the impact of the rating reductions for Maryland EXCELS; and
24 (2) experiential education requirements for child care providers.
25 (b) In conducting the review, the report from the Office of Program Evaluation
26 and Government Accountability of the Department of Legislative Services titled
27 “Evaluation of the Division of Early Childhood” shall be considered.
28 (c) On or before December 1, 2027, the Department shall report to the General
29 Assembly, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, on:
30 (1) findings from the review; and
31 (2) recommendations for statutory or regulatory changes to address
32 workforce and licensing challenges.

22 HOUSE BILL 1574
1 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
2 1, 2026. Section 2 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 3 2 years and, at the end
3 of June 30, 2029 2028, Section 2 of this Act, with no further action required by the General
4 Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
